lationship to the dominant international principles established by the humanitarian intervention of the 1990s and the UN’s Responsibility to Protect doctrine in 2005. Combining case studies of the interventions in Kosovo, Rwanda and Iraq, among others, and interviews with key actors including Gareth Evans and Bernard Kouchner, Staunton’s innovative theoretical framework offers a valuable tool for understanding the interplay between domestic and international norms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHumanitarian interventionzFrancexHistory. 0aIntervention (International law). 0aResponsibility to protect (International law)zFrance. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aForeign policy.  aFrance.  aHuman protection.  aHumanitarian intervention.  aNorm diffusion.  aNorm.  aResponsibility to protect.1 aStaunton, Eglantine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614241240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526142412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526142412/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles